    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. Parse timestamp columns as UTC datetimes. For metric.csv: aggregate by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and compute count, min timestamp, max timestamp, P95(value) and P5(value). Return up to 50 rows sorted by count descending. For trace.csv: aggregate by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute count, min timestamp, max timestamp, P95(value) and P5(value). Return up to 50 rows sorted by count descending. For log.csv: aggregate by (cmdb_id, log_name) and compute count, min timestamp, max timestamp, P95(value) and P5(value). Return up to 50 rows sorted by count descending. Also return a list of unique cmdb_id values found across all files and the earliest and latest timestamp present in each file. Keep outputs compact (no raw full time series), and store full tables in kernel variables for later steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous aggregation step we loaded metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv and found per-(cmdb_id, KPI) global statistics (count, p95, p5). The telemetry covers 2024-02-20 18:31:00 → 18:55:00 UTC (so within the incident window 18:28:18–18:58:18 we only have data from ~18:31–18:55). error_logs.csv contains no timestamped entries. We therefore should next perform metric-based anomaly detection within the incident window to narrow candidate faulty components before using traces/logs. The next actionable step is to detect metric anomalies per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) by comparing incident-window points to the previously computed global P95/P5 thresholds (global thresholds must be computed from the full series).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv: 1) Compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available metric series (do NOT filter by incident window when computing these thresholds). 2) Parse timestamps as UTC datetimes and filter metric rows to the incident window [2024-02-20 18:28:18 UTC, 2024-02-20 18:58:18 UTC]. 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within the incident window, mark rows as anomalies if value >= global P95 OR value <= global P5. 4) Aggregate anomaly results per (cmdb_id, kpi_name): count of anomaly points, earliest anomaly timestamp, latest anomaly timestamp, max(value), min(value), global_p95, global_p5. 5) Return two compact outputs: (A) anomaly summary aggregated table limited to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly count descending; (B) anomaly detail rows limited to top 100 rows sorted by timestamp ascending. Also store full filtered metric table and full anomaly table in kernel variables for later steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95/P5 thresholds per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full metric series, filtered metric data to the incident window, and marked anomaly points where value >= global P95 or value <= global P5. Results show many anomalies concentrated on the \"socket\" KPI (many components have anomaly_count=25 covering 18:31→18:55 UTC). This indicates widespread socket-level deviations across many services/nodes during the incident window. However, the root cause must be one of the provided candidate service components (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service). We need to narrow metric anomalies to those candidate services and inspect their KPIs (and later use trace and log telemetry) to find which one is faulty and why. Next step should therefore extract anomaly summary and sample anomaly detail restricted to those candidate cmdb_ids so we can see which KPIs are anomalous for the candidate services and whether anomalies are consecutive/full-window or sparse.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously stored anomaly_summary and metric_anomalies_full variables: 1) Filter anomaly_summary to only the candidate components: [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"]. Return up to 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count descending and include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, min_value, global_p95, global_p5. 2) Compute and return two small aggregates for these candidates: (A) total anomaly points across all their KPIs, (B) number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) groups affected. 3) Return sample anomaly detail rows from metric_anomalies_full for these candidate components limited to top 50 rows sorted by timestamp ascending and include columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, global_p95, global_p5. Store the filtered results in kernel variables for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-based anomaly detection and narrowed down affected candidate services. Metrics show notable anomalies across the five candidate services, with top metric signals: ts-travel-service (error KPI, concentrated 18:50–18:55), ts-order-service (socket, 18:32–18:53), ts-train-service (socket, 18:34–18:55), and ts-auth-service (cpu, latency-90, latency-50, socket, workload, mem). Total anomalies among candidates are 148 across 36 (component,KPI) groups. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace analysis to localize which candidate is the most downstream faulty service in call chains and to confirm propagation direction. We must compute global thresholds for trace features using the full trace series (not filtered), mark anomalies in the incident window, and then inspect trace anomalies for the five candidate services to see which trace signals (e.g., trace.to_ts-*.error_rate, duration_p95, row_count, etc.) show faults and their earliest timestamps. This will help choose the most downstream faulty service among the candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv: 1) Compute global P95 and P5 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available trace series (do NOT filter by incident window when computing these thresholds). 2) Parse timestamps as UTC datetimes and filter trace rows to the incident window [2024-02-20 18:28:18 UTC, 2024-02-20 18:58:18 UTC]. 3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) within the incident window, mark rows as anomalies if value >= global P95 OR value <= global P5. 4) Aggregate anomalies per (cmdb_id, trace_name): count, earliest anomaly timestamp, latest anomaly timestamp, max(value), min(value), global_p95, global_p5. 5) Return (A) an aggregated anomaly summary limited to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly count descending and including: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, min_value, global_p95, global_p5; (B) a sample anomaly detail table limited to top 50 rows sorted by timestamp ascending with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, global_p95, global_p5. 6) Restrict the returned rows to highlight the five candidate services [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] (i.e., include aggregated rows for these candidates first). Store full trace_filtered and trace_anomalies tables in kernel variables for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric analysis identified widespread anomalies across many services; narrowing to the five candidate services we observed 148 metric anomaly points across 36 (component,KPI) groups. Highest-severity signals among candidates: ts-travel-service had an error KPI concentrated at 18:50–18:55 UTC; ts-order-service and ts-train-service showed socket anomalies spanning mid-to-late window; ts-auth-service showed CPU and latency anomalies earlier in the window. Trace analysis (using global thresholds) produced many flagged trace.error_rate series; however, many error_rate series have global P95/P5 equal to 0.0 and observed values 0.0, which trivially mark all points as anomalies and are unhelpful. More useful trace anomalies include duration-based series (e.g., trace.to_ts-order-service.duration_mean in ts-travel-service exceeding its P95 at 18:31). To localize the root cause we still need logs: logs can show whether a service emitted errors or abnormal row/error counts that explain metric/trace anomalies and help identify the most downstream faulty service in call chains. Therefore the next step is focused log analysis for the five candidate services to see which service shows concrete error log signals or abnormal row_count/error_count patterns within the incident window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv: 1) Compute global P95 and P5 for each (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full available log series (do NOT filter by the incident window for threshold calculation). 2) Parse timestamps as UTC datetimes and filter log rows to the incident window [2024-02-20 18:28:18 UTC, 2024-02-20 18:58:18 UTC]. 3) Mark a row anomalous if value >= global P95 OR value <= global P5. 4) Aggregate anomalies per (cmdb_id, log_name): anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max(value), min(value), global_p95, global_p5. 5) Return two compact outputs: (A) anomaly summary table limited to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count descending with columns cmdb_id, log_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, min_value, global_p95, global_p5; (B) anomaly detail rows limited to top 100 rows sorted by timestamp ascending with columns timestamp, cmdb_id, log_name, value, global_p95, global_p5. 6) Additionally, filter both outputs to highlight the five candidate services [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] first (ensure candidate rows are included even if not top by count). Store full filtered log table and log_anomalies in kernel variables for subsequent correlation with metric and trace anomalies."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric, trace, and log anomaly detection and narrowed candidates to the five provided services. Metric signals: ts-auth-service shows CPU and latency anomalies; ts-order-service and ts-train-service show socket anomalies; ts-travel-service shows error and some trace-duration anomalies. Trace anomalies flagged many error_rate series (mostly zeros, uninformative), but there are useful duration anomalies (e.g., trace.to_ts-order-service.duration_mean in ts-travel-service at 18:31). Log analysis shows elevated log.row_count for several candidates (ts-travel-service, ts-route-service, ts-order-service, ts-auth-service) and log.error_count series are zero-valued and therefore trivially flagged. According to the localization rules, we must identify the most downstream faulty service in traces among the services that are metric-faulty. To do that we need a focused trace-level view of calls between candidate services (trace.to_ts-*/trace.from_ts-* series) and the earliest anomaly times per such call so we can determine which candidate is the downstream faulty component and when its fault first occurred.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace_anomaly summary/table (computed earlier), filter rows where trace_name contains any of the candidate service names: [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] and where trace_name indicates inter-service calls (strings containing 'to_ts-' or 'from_ts-'). Return up to 50 rows sorted by earliest_anomaly_ts ascending and include columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, min_value, global_p95, global_p5. Also, compute and return a compact per-candidate aggregation: for each candidate, earliest trace-anomaly timestamp (min of earliest_anomaly_ts) and total trace anomaly points (sum of anomaly_count). Keep outputs compact (<=50 rows). Store the filtered result in kernel variable trace_candidate_call_anomalies for next step."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection across metrics, traces, and logs. Metric anomalies for the five candidate services are abundant: ts-auth-service (CPU, latency, mem, socket, workload) with anomalies appearing earlier in the window; ts-order-service and ts-train-service show socket and latency anomalies; ts-travel-service shows error KPI anomalies concentrated later (18:50–18:55) plus some trace duration anomalies. Trace-edge aggregation shows many inter-service anomalous edges that target ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, and ts-travel-service with earliest incoming-call anomalies at ~2024-02-20T18:31:00Z; ts-auth-service had no incoming-call anomalies in the filtered inter-service edges. Many trace.error_rate series are uninformative because their global P95/P5 are 0.0 and the observed values are 0.0, marking them trivially anomalous. More meaningful signals are duration_mean/p95 and row_count anomalies on inter-service edges.

What we still need to determine: which of the five candidate services is the root cause (most downstream faulty service in call chains) and what the failure reason is (one of: high CPU, high memory, high disk I/O, network latency, network packet loss, socket error). To decide, we must correlate per-candidate earliest anomaly onset across metrics, traces (incoming calls), and logs to see which candidate is both metric-faulty and appears as downstream target in anomalous calls, and which shows the strongest/broadest deviation that could explain the failure propagation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For each of the five candidate services ["ts-auth-service","ts-order-service","ts-route-service","ts-train-service","ts-travel-service"] compute a compact per-candidate summary using the previously stored anomaly tables (metric_anomalies_full, trace_candidate_edges or candidate_target_summary, and log_anomalies):
1) earliest_metric_anomaly_ts = the minimum timestamp in metric_anomalies_full for that cmdb_id (within the incident-window filtered anomalies);
2) total_metric_anomaly_points = count of metric_anomalies_full rows for that cmdb_id;
3) earliest_log_anomaly_ts = the minimum timestamp in log_anomalies for that cmdb_id (if any), and total_log_anomaly_points = count of log_anomalies rows for that cmdb_id;
4) earliest_incoming_trace_anomaly_ts = the earliest incoming-call anomaly timestamp for that target from trace_candidate_edges/candidate_target_summary (NaT if none), and total_incoming_trace_anomaly_points = number of distinct anomalous incoming edges or sum of their total_anomaly_count (choose sum of total_anomaly_count);
5) For metric severity indication include the top 1 metric KPI (for that cmdb_id) by anomaly_count from candidate_anomaly_summary (or metric aggregate) and its anomaly_count (to indicate which resource shows most anomalies).
Return a compact table with one row per candidate and columns: cmdb_id, earliest_metric_anomaly_ts, total_metric_anomaly_points, top_metric_kpi, top_metric_kpi_anomaly_count, earliest_log_anomaly_ts, total_log_anomaly_points, earliest_incoming_trace_anomaly_ts, total_incoming_trace_anomaly_points. Limit output to these five rows. Store the result in kernel variable candidate_final_timeline."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated anomalies across metrics, traces, and logs and produced a per-candidate timeline. All five candidates show metric anomalies starting around 2024-02-20T18:31:00Z. ts-auth-service shows metric+log anomalies but no incoming anomalous calls (i.e., it is not observed as a downstream target in the filtered trace edges). ts-order-service, ts-train-service, ts-route-service, and ts-travel-service all have anomalous incoming trace edges (many anomalous incoming calls). Many trace.error_rate series are uninformative (P95/P5 == 0.0), but duration_mean/p95 and row_count anomalies on inter-service edges provide meaningful signals. According to the localization rules, the root cause service should be the most downstream faulty service within traces among the metric-identified faulty services. We are not yet certain which candidate is the most downstream because we need to inspect only the call edges among the five candidates to see which candidate is called by other faulty candidates (i.e., find candidate->candidate edges and their earliest anomaly times). This will let us pick the downstream-most faulty service and the earliest fault occurrence.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously stored aggregated inter-service edge table (trace_candidate_edges):\n1) Filter edges where both the source_cmdb_id and the target_service are in the candidate list: [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"].\n2) Return up to 20 rows sorted by earliest_anomaly_ts ascending with columns: source_cmdb_id, target_service, trace_metric_types, total_anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value, min_value.\n3) Also return a compact per-target summary for the five candidates indicating: target_service, has_incoming_from_candidates (True/False), earliest_incoming_from_candidate_ts (NaT if none), number_of_distinct_candidate_sources. Limit that summary to the five rows.\nStore the filtered edges in kernel variable candidate_to_candidate_edges and the per-target summary in candidate_incoming_from_candidates for the next step."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection across metrics, traces, and logs and produced a candidate-level timeline. Key points: all five candidates show metric anomalies starting ~2024-02-20T18:31:00Z. ts-auth shows metric+log anomalies but no incoming anomalous calls from other candidates. ts-order, ts-route, ts-train, ts-travel all have anomalous incoming calls; among candidate->candidate edges only ts-travel -> ts-train was detected (i.e., travel calls train). Many trace.error_rate series are uninformative (global P95/P5 == 0.0). Metric anomalies of interest include socket anomalies on ts-order and ts-train, CPU/latency anomalies on ts-auth, and error KPI on ts-travel. According to localization rules we should pick the most downstream faulty service in traces among metric-identified faulty services; travel->train suggests train could be downstream of travel. However, to decide which candidate is the root cause we need to compare severity of the faults (how strongly KPIs deviate from thresholds) and earliest non-trivial anomalous incoming-call evidence. Currently earliest timestamps are similar (~18:31) so severity (magnitude relative to global thresholds and persistence) will help decide. We need a compact severity comparison for the top metric KPI per candidate (max value, global P95, anomaly_count, and breach ratio) to rank which candidate shows the largest deviation and is the most plausible root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For each candidate [\"ts-auth-service\",\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-route-service\",\"ts-train-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] do the following using stored metric thresholds and incident-window filtered anomalies: 1) Identify the top metric KPI for that candidate by anomaly_count (use candidate_anomaly_summary or metric_anomalies_full). 2) For that KPI, return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value (within incident window), min_value (within incident window), global_p95, global_p5, and compute breach_ratio = (max_value - global_p95) / global_p95 (if global_p95 > 0, else set breach_ratio to NaN). 3) Also compute persistence = anomaly_count / number_of_minutes_present_in_incident_window_for_that_kpi (i.e., fraction of minutes in the window that were anomalous). Return a compact table with one row per candidate (5 rows) sorted by breach_ratio descending. Limit output to these five rows and store as candidate_severity_summary.",
}

